  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a psychological phenomenon where individuals from underrepresented groups experience anxiety or stress due to the fear of confirming negative stereotypes about their group's abilities in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics. As someone who grew up in a household where my father had a PhD and my mother had only completed lower secondary education, I witnessed firsthand how societal expectations can shape a person's confidence. Growing up in Naples, I saw many young women and people from minority backgrounds hesitate to pursue STEM fields because they believed they weren't 'smart enough' or 'capable enough.' This anxiety isn't just a feeling—it's a real barrier that can lead to underperformance and disengagement. I believe we absolutely must address stereotype threat in STEM. In my later years, I've read extensively on this topic and have seen how even small interventions can make a big difference. For example, creating mentorship programs that pair students with role models from similar backgrounds helps build confidence and shows that success is possible. Additionally, schools should implement inclusive curricula that highlight diverse contributions to STEM fields, not just the usual male-dominated narratives. It's important to recognize that stereotype threat isn't just an issue for students—it affects professionals as well. As a retired woman who has spent her life reading novels and watching football matches, I've learned that anxiety can be managed through support systems. We need to foster environments where everyone feels safe to explore their interests without fear of judgment. The key is to start early, with educators and parents working together to challenge stereotypes and promote a growth mindset. After all, if we want to build a future where everyone has equal opportunities in STEM, we must confront stereotype threat head-on.",
